The '''BMW R1200GS''' and '''R1200GS Adventure''' are [[motorcycle]]s manufactured in [[Berlin]], Germany by [[BMW Motorrad]], part of the [[BMW]] group. It is one of the [[BMW GS]] family of [[dual sport]] motorcycles. Both motorcycles feature a 1170&nbsp;cc, 2-cylinder [[boxer engine]] with 4-valves per cylinder. The Adventure features a larger capacity fuel tank and longer travel suspension.

==History==
At its launch in 2004, the R1200GS was {{convert|30|kg|lb|abbr=on}} lighter than the [[BMW R1150GS|R1150GS]] it replaced,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorbikes/2726676/Lightweight-boxer-packs-a-heavy-punch.html | title= 
Lightweight boxer packs a heavy punch | last= Ash | first= Kevin | publisher= [[Daily Telegraph]] | date= 14 February 2007 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref> 
and produced {{convert|100|bhp|abbr=on}}, an increase of 19%. BMW continued to produce the [[BMW R1150GS|R1150GS Adventure]], releasing a final run-out special edition model,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.motorcyclenews.com/MCN/News/newsresults/archive/86493/87362/87444/87450/?&R=EPI-87450 | publisher= [[Motorcycle News]] | date= 20 May 2005 | title= BMW Adventure special | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-08}}</ref> 
before launching the R1200GS Adventure at the end of 2005 for the 2006 [[model year]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.biker247.com/News/4106.asp | title= THE NEW BMW R1200 GS ADVENTURE | date= 29 October 2005 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-08}}</ref>

In 2007, upgrades were made to both models for the 2008 model year. Power was increased to {{convert|105|bhp|abbr=on}}, a new Integral ABS II [[anti-lock braking system]] was released without servo assistance and new options were added including  electronic [[Suspension (motorcycle)|suspension]] adjustment (ESA) and [[Electronic stability control|automatic stability control]] (ASC).<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.viamichelin.co.uk/viamichelin/gbr/tpl/mag5/art20080215/htm/mobil-moto-BMW-R-1200-GS.htm | publisher= ViaMichelin | title= BMW R 1200 GS 2008 | last= Weyland | first= Thierry | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.totalmotorcycle.com/photos/2008models/2008models-BMW-R1200GS.htm | publisher= Total Motorcycle | title= 2008 BMW R1200GS | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-08}}</ref>

==Popularity==
The R1200GS is the best selling motorcycle that BMW have built&ndash;on 3 August 2007 it produced the 100,000th model.<ref name="GS 100K">{{cite web |url= http://www.webbikeworld.com/BMW-motorcycles/bmw-r1200-gs.htm?fromrss=1 | title= BMW's 100,000th R&nbsp;1200&nbsp;GS | work= webBikeWorld (from BMW press release) | date= 3 August 2007 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-02-03}}</ref> In 2006 the R1200GS was the best selling motorcycle in the United Kingdom. The two models had combined sales of 2,227 units, compared with the next best selling bike, the [[Honda Fireblade]] which sold 2,067 units.<ref name=ego>{{cite web | url= http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorbikes/2745494/Egos-go-for-off-road-cred.html | publisher= [[Daily Telegraph]] | last= Ash | first= Kevin | date= 2 February 2007 | title= Egos go for off road cred | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
Nearly one third of the 100,000 units sold by BMW Motorrad worldwide in 2006 were R1200GS.<ref name=ego/>
In 2008, the R1200GS was once again BMW's best selling motorcycle, with 22,845 standard models and 12,460 Adventure models being delivered.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.motorcycle.com/news/bmw-positive-about-sales-figures-87856.html | publisher= motorcycle.com | title= BMW positive about sales figures | date= 22 January 2009 | dateformat= dmy | accessdate= 2 February 2009}}</ref>

[[File:BMW R1200GS track.jpg|thumb|left|A dual purpose bike can be used on track as well as off road]]
In 2007, the bike was popularised by [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Charley Boorman]], who used the Adventure model for a trip from [[John O'Groats]] in Scotland to [[Cape Agulhas]] in South Africa.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.motorcyclenews.com/MCN/News/newsresults/mcn/2007/May/may-1-to-may-6/may0407longwaydown/?&R=EPI-90987 | publisher= [[Motorcycle News]] | last= Rayner | first= Tom | date= 4 May 2007 | title= Long Way Down | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2008-12-28}}</ref> The trip was documented in a book and television series ''[[Long Way Down]]''.

The R1200GS was featured in several episodes the [[BBC Two]] television programme ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Cookbook]]'', ridden by chefs Dave Myers and Si King.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.worldofbmw.com/content/article.asp?article=529&artDate=31/05/2006%2014:08:37 | date= 31 May 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-09 | title= Two Hairy Bikers and one lucky winner | publisher= World of BMW}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz/s/1063073_crumbs__more_hairy_moments | title= Crumbs - more hairy moments | publisher= [[Manchester Evening News]] | last= Welch | first= Andy | date= 18 August 2008 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-09}}</ref>

==Safety issues==
The R1200GS has been affected by a number of safety issues since launch. The United Kingdom [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency]] (VOSA) has issued nine separate [[Product recall|vehicle recalls]] covering the front brakes,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=2FB2C9140B693C4980257448004A4385&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2008/019 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 12 June 2008 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
[[anti-lock braking system]],<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=7802F713BF36E6898025713B003ECCD2 | title= Recall RM/2006/020 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 14 March 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=3931D4B7E0CCF9208025713B003F3828&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2006/021 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 14 March 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
throttle cable,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=971223298BFD22C9802570450036D627&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2005/015 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 18 March 2005  | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
fuel pump,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=A5DDA35C0000D4C8802570450037D9C0&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2005/016 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 4 February 2005 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
clutch,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=3EEE463E2EDBA5438025713B004149C9&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2006/023 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 14 March 2006  | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref>
final drive assembly,<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=1E7A9935686A555A802571F1002D99D0&freeText=Blank | title= Recall RM/2006/037 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 12 September 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 2009-01-07}}</ref> 
brake pipes,<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=040430B075E1C5DB802575070033B8DA&freeText=Blank&tx=VOSA | title= Recall RM/2008/048 | date= 17 November 2008 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 12 September 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 22 May 2009}}</ref>
and gearbox.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.vosa.gov.uk/vosa/apps/recalls/searches/expand.asp?uniqueID=50F3CCDB41A85603802575070034FC71&freeText=Blank&tx=VOSA | title= Recall RM/2008/050 | date= 28 March 2008 | publisher= [[Vehicle and Operator Services Agency|VOSA]] | date= 12 September 2006 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate= 22 May 2009}}</ref> 
Similar recalls have been issued in other countries.

